"Title": "Tracheal Resection of a Stomal Stricture and Repair Following a Tracheostomy",
"Authors": {
    "1": "Patterson GA", "2": "Yee A"
},
"Author Information": {
    "1": "Division of Cardiothoracic Surgery, Washington University, St. Louis, Missouri", "2": "Division of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery, Washington University, St. Louis, Missouri"
},
"Description": "Tracheotomy and endotracheal intubation continues to be most common cause for tracheal stenosis and management involves tracheal resection and reapproximation. In this case, the patient presented with a history of multiple cardiac surgical procedures. She undergone a tracheostomy and developed recent symptoms of stridor. Imaging studies demonstrated a typical tracheostomy and stromal stricture. Surgical management involved tracheal resection and primary anastomosis. This video details the specifics for a tracheal resection from incision to closure."
}

